{"title_page": "Carl Salemann", "text_new": "{{short description|Russian scholar}}\n{{Infobox person/Wikidata|fetchwikidata=ALL}}\n'''Carl Hermann Salemann''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u0430\u0440\u043b \u0413\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0417\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0430\u043d}}, '''Karl Germanovitsh Zaleman'''; {{OldStyleDateDY|9 January|1850|28 December 1849}} \u2014 {{OldStyleDate|13 December|1916|30 November}}) was a Russian [[Iranistics|Iranist scholar]]. He was an academician of [[Saint Petersburg Academy of Sciences]] (1895) and a director of [[Asiatic Museum]] of the Academy of Sciences (1890\u20141916).\n\n== Biography ==\nSalemann was a [[Baltic Germans|Baltic German]], born in Revel (now [[Tallinn]], [[Estonia]]).<ref name=\"iranica\">{{iranica|salemann-carl-hermann|Salemann, Carl Hermann|D. Durkin-Meisterernst}}</ref>\n\nHe studied at {{ill|Oriental Faculty of Saint Petersburg University|lt=Oriental Faculty|ru|\u0412\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0444\u0430\u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0435\u0442 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442\u0430}} of [[Saint Petersburg Imperial University]], Arabic-Persian-Turkish and the Sanskrit-Persian sections, in 1867\u20131871.<ref name=\"iranica\" /> He defended a thesis on the [[quatrain]]s of [[Khaqani]] and obtained master's degree on Persion literature in 1875.<ref name=\"esbe\">{{\u0412\u0422-\u042d\u0421\u0411\u0415|\u0417\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0430\u043d, \u041a\u0430\u0440\u043b \u0413\u0435\u043d\u0440\u0438\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|[[Nikolay Veselovsky|\u041d. \u0418. \u0412\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1875, he became an assistant university librarian, and in 1879, he was promoted to full librarian.<ref name=\"iranica\" />\n\nSince 1876 till his death Salemann taught [[Zend]] and [[Middle Persian]] literature on Oriental Faculty.<ref name=\"iranica\" /><ref name=\"esbe\" /> He held a position of [[Privatdozent]].<ref name=\"esbe\" />\n\nIn 1882, he was elected a member of [[Imperial Russian Archaeological Society]].\n\nHe was also elected an adjunct member of [[Saint Petersburg Academy of Sciences]] (specializing in Asiatic literature and history) in 1886, an extraordinary academician in 1890, an ordinary academician in 1895.<ref name=\"ivrran\">[http://www.orientalstudies.ru/rus/index.php?option=com_personalities&Itemid=74&person=695 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u043b \u0413\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0417\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0430\u043d] // [[Institute of Oriental Manuscripts of the Russian Academy of Sciences]]</ref>\n\nSince 1890 till his death he was a director of [[Asiatic Museum]] of the Academy of Sciences.<ref name=\"ivrran\" /> In this position he collected munuscripts and books and published descriptions of newly acquired items, as well as prepared catalogues of the museum.<ref name=\"iranica\" />\n\nIn 1890, he became a librarian of second section of the library of the Academy of Sciences.<ref name=\"iranica\" /><ref name=\"esbe\" />\n\nIn 1902, Salemann became an honorary professor of [[University of Giessen]]. In 1903, he became a member of the [[Russian committee for the Study of Central and Eastern Asia]]. In 1904, he became a corresponding member of the [[Hungarian Academy of Sciences]]. In 1908, he became an honorary member of the [[Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland|Royal Asiatic Society]].<ref name=\"iranica\" />\n\n== Bibliography ==\nMain works of Salemann:<ref name=\"esbe\" />\n* \u00abUeber eine Parsenhandschrift der K. Oeffentl. Bibliothek zu St. Petersburg\u00bb (\u00abTravaux de la 3-\u0435 session du Congr\u00e8s international des Orientalistes\u00bb, vol. II, [[Leiden]], 1879);\n* \u00abMittelpersische Studien\u00bb (\u00abBulletin de l\u2019Acad\u00e9mie\u00bb, 1886);\n* \u00abScham-si-Fachrii lexicon Persicum\u00bb ([[Kazan]], 1887);\n* \u00abBericht \u00fcber die Ausgabe des Mi\u2019jar i Jamali\u00bb (\u00abBulletin de l\u2019Acad\u00e9mie\u00bb. 1888);\n* \u00abPersische Grammatik mit Litteratur, Chrestomathie und Glossar\u00bb (together with V. Zhukovsky, [[Leipzig]]., 1889);\n* \u00ab\u041a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430, \u0441 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043c \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0438 \u0431\u0438\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0438\u00bb (together with V. Zhukovsky, [[Saint Petersburg]], 1890);\n* \u00abNoch einmal die Seldschukischen Verse\u00bb (1890, \u00abBulletin de l\u2019Acad\u00e9mie\u00bb).\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Imperial Russian philologists]]\n[[Category:Full Members of the St Petersburg Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Iranologists]]\n[[Category:Saint Petersburg State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Baltic-German people]]\n[[Category:Directors of Asiatic Museum]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Russian scholar}}\n{{Infobox person/Wikidata|fetchwikidata=ALL}}\n'''Carl Hermann Salemann''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u0430\u0440\u043b \u0413\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0417\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0430\u043d}}, '''Karl Germanovitsh Zaleman'''; {{OldStyleDateDY|9 January|1850|28 December 1849}} \u2014 {{OldStyleDate|13 December|1916|30 November}}) was a Russian [[Iranistics|Iranist scholar]]. He was an academician of [[Saint Petersburg Academy of Sciences]] (1895) and a director of [[Asiatic Museum]] of the Academy of Sciences (1890\u20141916).\n\n== Biography ==\nSalemann was a [[Baltic Germans|Baltic German]], born in Revel (now [[Tallinn]], [[Estonia]])<ref name=\"iranica\">{{iranica|salemann-carl-hermann|Salemann, Carl Hermann|D. Durkin-Meisterernst}}</ref>.\n\nHe studied at {{ill|Oriental Faculty of Saint Petersburg University|lt=Oriental Faculty|ru|\u0412\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0444\u0430\u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0435\u0442 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442\u0430}} of [[Saint Petersburg Imperial University]], Arabic-Persian-Turkish and the Sanskrit-Persian sections, in 1867-1871<ref name=\"iranica\" />. He defended a thesis on the [[quatrain]]s of [[Khaqani]] and obtained master's degree on Persion literature in 1875<ref name=\"esbe\">{{\u0412\u0422-\u042d\u0421\u0411\u0415|\u0417\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0430\u043d, \u041a\u0430\u0440\u043b \u0413\u0435\u043d\u0440\u0438\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|[[Nikolay Veselovsky|\u041d. \u0418. \u0412\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439]]}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1875, he became an assistant university librarian, and in 1879, he was promoted to full librarian<ref name=\"iranica\" />.\n\nSince 1876 till his death Salemann taught [[Zend]] and [[Middle Persian]] literature on Oriental Faculty<ref name=\"iranica\" /><ref name=\"esbe\" />. He held a position of [[Privatdozent]]<ref name=\"esbe\" />.\n\nIn 1882, he was elected a member of [[Imperial Russian Archaeological Society]].\n\nHe was also elected an adjunct member of [[Saint Petersburg Academy of Sciences]] (specializing in Asiatic literature and history) in 1886, an extra-ordinary academician in 1890, an ordinary academician in 1895<ref name=\"ivrran\">[http://www.orientalstudies.ru/rus/index.php?option=com_personalities&Itemid=74&person=695 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u043b \u0413\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0417\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0430\u043d] // [[Institute of Oriental Manuscripts of the Russian Academy of Sciences]]</ref>.\n\nSince 1890 till his death he was a director of [[Asiatic Museum]] of the Academy of Sciences<ref name=\"ivrran\" />. In this position he collected munuscripts and books and published descriptions of newly acquired items, as well as prepared catalogues of the museum<ref name=\"iranica\" />.\n\nIn 1890, he became a librarian of second section of the library of the Academy of Sciences<ref name=\"iranica\" /><ref name=\"esbe\" />.\n\nIn 1902, Salemann became a honorary professor of [[University of Giessen]]. In 1903, he became a member of the [[Russian committee for the Study of Central and Eastern Asia]]. In 1904, he became a corresponding member of the [[Hungarian Academy of Sciences]]. In 1908, he became a honorary member of the [[Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland|Royal Asiatic Society]]<ref name=\"iranica\" />.\n\n== Bibliography ==\nMain works of Salemann<ref name=\"esbe\" />:\n* \u00abUeber eine Parsenhandschrift der K. Oeffentl. Bibliothek zu St. Petersburg\u00bb (\u00abTravaux de la 3-\u0435 session du Congr\u00e8s international des Orientalistes\u00bb, vol. II, [[Leiden]], 1879);\n* \u00abMittelpersische Studien\u00bb (\u00abBulletin de l\u2019Acad\u00e9mie\u00bb, 1886);\n* \u00abScham-si-Fachrii lexicon Persicum\u00bb ([[Kazan]], 1887);\n* \u00abBericht \u00fcber die Ausgabe des Mi\u2019jar i Jamali\u00bb (\u00abBulletin de l\u2019Acad\u00e9mie\u00bb. 1888);\n* \u00abPersische Grammatik mit Litteratur, Chrestomathie und Glossar\u00bb (together with V. Zhukovsky, [[Leipzig]]., 1889);\n* \u00ab\u041a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430, \u0441 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043c \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0438 \u0431\u0438\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0438\u00bb (together with V. Zhukovsky, [[Saint Petersburg]], 1890);\n* \u00abNoch einmal die Seldschukischen Verse\u00bb (1890, \u00abBulletin de l\u2019Acad\u00e9mie\u00bb).\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Imperial Russian philologists]]\n[[Category:Full Members of the St Petersburg Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Iranologists]]\n[[Category:Saint Petersburg State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Baltic-German people]]\n[[Category:Directors of Asiatic Museum]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: extra-ordinary \u2192 extraordinary, a honorary \u2192 an honorary (2), 1867-1871 \u2192 1867\u20131871", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Salemann"}
{"title_page": "Into the Rainbow", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Into the Rainbow\n| image          = The Wonder (film) poster.jpeg\n| alt            = The Wonder 3D\n| caption        = Teaser poster\n| film name      = {{film name\n| chinese        = \u5947\u8ff9\uff1a\u8ffd\u9010\u5f69\u8679}}\n| director       = Norman Stone <br>Gary Mak\n| producer       = Iain Brown<br>Richard Fletcher<br>Emma Slade<br>Zhou Difei<!-- or: |producers = -->\n| writer         = [[Ashley Sidaway]]<br>[[Robert Sidaway (actor)|Robert Sidaway]]<br>Lindsay Edmonds\n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| based on       = \n| starring       = [[Willow Shields]]<br>[[Maria Grazia Cucinotta]]\n| narrator       = <!-- or: |narrators = -->\n| music          = Tom McLeod\n| cinematography = Richard Bluck\n| editing        = Peter Roberts\n| studio         = Beijing Tianrun Media<br>Libertine Pictures<br>TW Films<ref name=Frater/><!-- or: |production companies = -->\n| distributor    = Stellar Mega Films (China)<br>Rialto Distribution (New Zealand)<ref name=Frater/><!-- or: |distributors = -->\n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|2017|04|08|TIFF Kids}}<br> {{film date|df=yes|2017|11|01|Canada}}\n| runtime        = 88 mins \n| country        = China<br>New Zealand\n| language       = English\n| budget         = US$20 million<ref name=Frater/> \n| gross          = <!--(please use condensed and rounded values, e.g. \"\u00a311.6 million\" not \"\u00a311,586,221\")-->\n}}\n'''''Into the Rainbow''''' (titled: \u5947\u8ff9\uff1a\u8ffd\u9010\u5f69\u8679; The Wonder: Chasing Rainbows) is a [[fantasy film|fantasy]] [[adventure film|adventure]] film directed by Norman Stone, co-directed by Gary Wing-Lun Mak, and written by [[Ashley Sidaway]] and [[Robert Sidaway (actor)|Robert Sidaway]]. The film stars [[Willow Shields]], [[Leo Wu|\u5434\u78ca (Wu Lei), [[Maria Grazia Cucinotta]], [[Joe Chen|\u9648\u4e54\u6069 (Joe Chen)]], Jacqueline Joe, [[Archie Kao]] and [[Christy Chung|\u949f\u4e3d\u7f07 (Christy Chung)]]. The film is a [[international co-production|co-production]] between [[China]] and [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.screendaily.com/news/afm-metro-international-heads-into-the-rainbow/5110878.article|title=AFM: Metro International heads 'Into The Rainbow'|date=2 November 2016|first=Andreas|last=Wiseman|accessdate=4 October 2018|work=[[Screen Daily]]}}</ref><ref name=Frater>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2015/film/asia/archie-kao-joins-china-the-wonder-1201629534/|title= Archie Kao Joins China-New Zealand Fantasy Film \u2018The Wonder\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|author= Patrick Frater|date= 29 October 2015|accessdate= 29 October 2015|work= [[variety.com]]}}</ref> The film was shot in [[3D film|3D]].\n\n==Plot==\nTwo troubled teenage girls, Rachel and Grace, discover an incredible natural phenomenon and find themselves transported inside a super-powered rainbow to China. Due to this, they disturbed nature's balance and are chased down by an obsessed scientist and her mysterious international organization. Using Rachel's  connection to the energy of the rainbow and with help from their new friend Xiao Cheng, they must race against time to  restore nature's balance before catastrophic storms destroy the entire Pacific and threaten the world.<ref name=Frater/>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Willow Shields]] as Rachel\n*[[Maria Grazia Cucinotta]] as Julia Bianchi \n*[[Leo Wu]] as Xiao Cheng \n*Jacqueline Joe as Grace\n*[[Joe Chen]] as Lian\n*[[Archie Kao]] as Song \n*[[Christy Chung]] as Mei \n*[[Emmett Skilton]] as Tom Williams\n*[[Tania Nolan]] as Lindsay \n*[[Bruce Hopkins (actor)|Bruce Hopkins]] as Major \n*[[Chelsie Preston Crayford]] as Susan \n*Peter Feeney as Scientist \n*Colin Moy as Ben\n*Tessa Rao as Koia \n*Sophie McIntosh as Koia's girl\n*Sylvia Rands as Gini  \n*Talia Pua as Sea Shore customer \n*Scarlett Sills as young Rachel\n\n==Production==\nThe film was shot in [[Qingdao]], China and [[Auckland]], New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/the-wonder-3d-fantasy-heads-for-china-shoot/5094686.article|title='The Wonder' 3D fantasy heads for China shoot|author=Andreas Wiseman|accessdate= 14 February 2017|work= [[Screen Daily]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2016/artisans/production/wanda-qingdao-production-incentives-1201907449/|title= Wanda\u2019s Qingdao Complex Is Set to Lure Producers With Hefty 40% Incentive|author= Variety Staff|date= 4 November 2016|accessdate= 6 November 2016|work= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was shown at the TIFF Kids International Film Festival during April 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://torontoguardian.com/2017/03/tiff-kids-film-fest-2/|title= TIFF Kids Film Fest is coming to Toronto and here\u2019s what we\u2019re excited to see!|author= Sonya Davidson|date= 15 March 2017|accessdate= 21 March 2017|work= Toronto Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tiff.net/films/into-the-rainbow/|title= Into the Rainbow|accessdate= 21 March 2017|work= TIFF Kids International}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://cinemaaxis.com/2017/03/02/smurfs-ballerina-and-more-play-20th-anniversary-of-tiff-kids-international-film-festival/|title= Smurfs, Ballerina, and more play 20th Anniversary of TIFF Kids International Film Festival|author= Courtney Small|date= 2 March 2017|accessdate= 21 March 2017|work= Cinema Axis}}</ref>\n\nThe film received its United States. Premiere with a Gala Screening at the Savannah Film Festival on 4 November 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://deadline.com/2017/10/scad-film-festival-2017-lineup-movies-1202179796/|title= SCAD Savannah Film Festival Lineup Set|author= Bruce Haring|date= 2 October 2017|accessdate= 6 October 2017|work= Deadline Hollywood}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://filmfest.scad.edu/schedule|title= SCAD Savannah Film Festival Schedule|accessdate= 6 October 2017}}</ref> and was Opening Night film of the Asia Pacific Film Festival in Auckland on 28 October 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.apff.org.nz/2017-nzapff.html|title= Asia Pacific Film Festival 2017|accessdate= 26 October 2017|work= Asia Pacific Film Festival 2017 Schedule}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU1710/S00102/auckland-to-host-5th-nz-asia-pacific-film-festival.html |title= Auckland to Host 5th NZ Asia Pacific Film Festival|accessdate= 26 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter a limited theatrical release in China during April 2019, <ref>{{cite web |url= https://chengdu-expat.com/9-foreign-films-in-chengdu-april-2019/ |title= 9 Foreign Films in Chengdu|accessdate= 30 March 2020}}</ref> the film was scheduled for a nationwide release on January 25, 2020, during the Chinese New Year holidays. <ref>{{cite web |url= https://chinafilminsider.com/headlines-from-china-a-look-at-2020-chinese-new-year-films/ |title= A Look at 2020 Chinese New Year Films|accessdate= 30 March 2020|work=China Insider}}</ref> Due to the coronavirus outbreak, the release was delayed and the film made available through the Smart Cinema online app. <ref>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2020/digital/asia/china-virus-crisis-video-streamer-online-games-donnie-yen-1203488032/ |title= China\u2019s Virus Crisis Hands Initiative to Video Streamers, Games Firms|accessdate= 30 March 2020|work= [[variety.com]]}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url= https://m.weibo.cn/detail/4464670071324959 |title= Smart Cinema release|accessdate= 30 March 2020}}</ref> It was subsequently announced that the film's theatrical release in China was scheduled for April 5, 2020. <ref>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2020/film/asia/cinemas-china-reopen-coronavirus-recedes-1203542000/ |title= China Theaters Begin To Reopen|accessdate= 30 March 2020|work= [[variety.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Novel==\n\nA novel titled The Wonder, Into The Rainbow was written by [[Robert Sidaway (actor)|Robert Sidaway]] and [[Ashley Sidaway]] based on the story and screenplay. <ref>{{cite web |url= https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Wonder_Into_the_Rainbow.html?id=_H1tswEACAAJ&source=kp_book_description |title= The Wonder Into The Rainbow|accessdate= 29 March 2020|work= Google Books}}</ref> The book includes a foreword written by [[Willow Shields]]. It was first published by Steam Press, part of the Eunoia Publishing Group, in October 2017. In 2019 it was made available as an ebook in both English and Simplified Chinese. <ref>{{cite web |url= https://fivedogsbooks.com/the-wonder-into-the-rainbow-robert-sidaway-ashley-sidaway-9780994131676 |title= The Wonder book|accessdate= 30 March 2020| work=Five Dogs Books}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|2374684}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Into the Rainbow}}\n[[Category:2010s fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:2017 3D films]]\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:Chinese 3D films]]\n[[Category:Chinese fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:Chinese films]]\n[[Category:Films set in China]]\n[[Category:Films shot in China]]\n[[Category:New Zealand 3D films]]\n[[Category:New Zealand fantasy films]]\n[[Category:New Zealand films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Into the Rainbow\n| image          = The Wonder (film) poster.jpeg\n| alt            = The Wonder 3D\n| caption        = Teaser poster\n| film name      = {{film name\n| chinese        = \u5947\u8ff9\uff1a\u8ffd\u9010\u5f69\u8679}}\n| director       = Norman Stone <br>Gary Mak\n| producer       = Iain Brown<br>Richard Fletcher<br>Emma Slade<br>Zhou Difei<!-- or: |producers = -->\n| writer         = [[Ashley Sidaway]]<br>[[Robert Sidaway (actor)|Robert Sidaway]]<br>Lindsay Edmonds\n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| based on       = \n| starring       = [[Willow Shields]]<br>[[Maria Grazia Cucinotta]]\n| narrator       = <!-- or: |narrators = -->\n| music          = Tom McLeod\n| cinematography = Richard Bluck\n| editing        = Peter Roberts\n| studio         = Beijing Tianrun Media<br>Libertine Pictures<br>TW Films<ref name=Frater/><!-- or: |production companies = -->\n| distributor    = Stellar Mega Films (China)<br>Rialto Distribution (New Zealand)<ref name=Frater/><!-- or: |distributors = -->\n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|2017|04|08|TIFF Kids}}<br> {{film date|df=yes|2017|11|01|Canada}}\n| runtime        = 88 mins \n| country        = China<br>New Zealand\n| language       = English\n| budget         = US$20 million<ref name=Frater/> \n| gross          = <!--(please use condensed and rounded values, e.g. \"\u00a311.6 million\" not \"\u00a311,586,221\")-->\n}}\n'''''Into the Rainbow''''' (titled: \u5947\u8ff9\uff1a\u8ffd\u9010\u5f69\u8679; The Wonder: Chasing Rainbows) is a [[fantasy film|fantasy]] [[adventure film|adventure]] film directed by Norman Stone,co-directed by Gary Wing-Lun Mak, and written by [[Ashley Sidaway]] and [[Robert Sidaway (actor)|Robert Sidaway]]. The film stars [[Willow Shields]],\u00a0\u5434\u78ca (Wu Lei), [[Maria Grazia Cucinotta]],\u00a0 \u9648\u4e54\u6069 (Joe Chen), Jacqueline Joe, Archie Kao and \u949f\u4e3d\u7f07 (Christy Chung). The film is a [[international co-production|co-production]] between [[China]] and [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.screendaily.com/news/afm-metro-international-heads-into-the-rainbow/5110878.article|title=AFM: Metro International heads 'Into The Rainbow'|date=2 November 2016|first=Andreas|last=Wiseman|accessdate=4 October 2018|work=[[Screen Daily]]}}</ref><ref name=Frater>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2015/film/asia/archie-kao-joins-china-the-wonder-1201629534/|title= Archie Kao Joins China-New Zealand Fantasy Film \u2018The Wonder\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|author= Patrick Frater|date= 29 October 2015|accessdate= 29 October 2015|work= [[variety.com]]}}</ref> The film was shot in [[3D film|3D]].\n\n==Plot==\nTwo troubled teenage girls, Rachel and Grace, discover an incredible natural phenomenon and find themselves transported inside a super-powered rainbow to China. Due to this, they disturbed nature's balance and are chased down by an obsessed scientist and her mysterious international organization. Using Rachel's  connection to the energy of the rainbow and with help from their new friend Xiao Cheng, they must race against time to  restore nature's balance before catastrophic storms destroy the entire Pacific and threaten the world.<ref name=Frater/>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Willow Shields]] as Rachel\n*[[Maria Grazia Cucinotta]] as Julia Bianchi \n*[[Leo Wu]] as Xiao Cheng \n*Jacqueline Joe as Grace\n*[[Joe Chen]] as Lian\n*[[Archie Kao]] as Song \n*[[Christy Chung]] as Mei \n*[[Emmett Skilton]] as Tom Williams\n*[[Tania Nolan]] as Lindsay \n*[[Bruce Hopkins (actor)|Bruce Hopkins]] as Major \n*[[Chelsie Preston Crayford]] as Susan \n*Peter Feeney as Scientist \n*Colin Moy as Ben\n*Tessa Rao as Koia \n*Sophie McIntosh as Koia's girl\n*Sylvia Rands as Gini  \n*Talia Pua as Sea Shore customer \n*Scarlett Sills as young Rachel\n\n==Production==\nThe film was shot in [[Qingdao]], China and [[Auckland]], New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/the-wonder-3d-fantasy-heads-for-china-shoot/5094686.article|title='The Wonder' 3D fantasy heads for China shoot|author=Andreas Wiseman|accessdate= 14 February 2017|work= [[Screen Daily]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2016/artisans/production/wanda-qingdao-production-incentives-1201907449/|title= Wanda\u2019s Qingdao Complex Is Set to Lure Producers With Hefty 40% Incentive|author= Variety Staff|date= 4 November 2016|accessdate= 6 November 2016|work= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was shown at the TIFF Kids International Film Festival during April 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://torontoguardian.com/2017/03/tiff-kids-film-fest-2/|title= TIFF Kids Film Fest is coming to Toronto and here\u2019s what we\u2019re excited to see!|author= Sonya Davidson|date= 15 March 2017|accessdate= 21 March 2017|work= Toronto Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tiff.net/films/into-the-rainbow/|title= Into the Rainbow|accessdate= 21 March 2017|work= TIFF Kids International}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://cinemaaxis.com/2017/03/02/smurfs-ballerina-and-more-play-20th-anniversary-of-tiff-kids-international-film-festival/|title= Smurfs, Ballerina, and more play 20th Anniversary of TIFF Kids International Film Festival|author= Courtney Small|date= 2 March 2017|accessdate= 21 March 2017|work= Cinema Axis}}</ref>\n\nThe film received its U.S. Premiere with a Gala Screening at the Savannah Film Festival on 4 November 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://deadline.com/2017/10/scad-film-festival-2017-lineup-movies-1202179796/|title= SCAD Savannah Film Festival Lineup Set|author= Bruce Haring|date= 2 October 2017|accessdate= 6 October 2017|work= Deadline Hollywood}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://filmfest.scad.edu/schedule|title= SCAD Savannah Film Festival Schedule|accessdate= 6 October 2017}}</ref> and was Opening Night film of the Asia Pacific Film Festival in Auckland on 28 October 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.apff.org.nz/2017-nzapff.html|title= Asia Pacific Film Festival 2017|accessdate= 26 October 2017|work= Asia Pacific Film Festival 2017 Schedule}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU1710/S00102/auckland-to-host-5th-nz-asia-pacific-film-festival.html |title= Auckland to Host 5th NZ Asia Pacific Film Festival|accessdate= 26 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter a limited theatrical release in China during March 2019, the film was scheduled for a nationwide release on January 25, 2020, during the Chinese New Year holidays. Due to the coronavirus outbreak, the release was delayed and the film made available through the Smart Cinema online app. It was subsequently announced that the film's theatrical release in China was scheduled for April 5, 2020.\n\n==Novel==\n\nA novel titled The Wonder, Into The Rainbow was written by [[Robert Sidaway (actor)|Robert Sidaway]] and [[Ashley Sidaway]] based on the story and screenplay. The book includes a foreword written by [[Willow Shields]]. It was first published by Steam Press, part of the Eunoia Publishing Group, in October 2017. In 2019 it was made available as an ebook in both English and Simplified Chinese.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|2374684}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Into the Rainbow}}\n[[Category:2010s fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:2017 3D films]]\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:Chinese 3D films]]\n[[Category:Chinese fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:Chinese films]]\n[[Category:Films set in China]]\n[[Category:Films shot in China]]\n[[Category:New Zealand 3D films]]\n[[Category:New Zealand fantasy films]]\n[[Category:New Zealand films]]\n", "name_user": "HudsonHarbor94", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Into_the_Rainbow"}
